{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507009"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:49:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:49:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2598"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2598"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.13,0.06,0.02,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42700"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2598"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27644"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2898"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30084"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42700"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man patient is admitted to the hospital with acute cholecystitis. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination his blood pressure is 126/82, pulse 90/min and temperature 38.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There is tenderness in the right upper quadrant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment is started with intravenous antibiotics (cefazolin 2g IV) but he spikes more fevers overnight. Blood cultures are taken and grow \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus bovis\u003C/em\u003E.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following underlying occult malignancies is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colorectal cancer","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Gastric cancer","Renal cell carcinoma","Cholangiocarcinoma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAny culture result such as this should raise great suspicion as it is not of the usual organisms associated with cholecystitis. The usual organisms are \u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli, Enterobacter cloacae, Proteus vulgaris \u003C/em\u003Eand\u003Cem\u003E Streptococcus faecalis\u003C/em\u003E. Empirical antibiotic therapy is aimed at this infection with metronidazole and ceftriaxone; another antibiotic that may be added is gentamicin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis question focusses on the pertinence of such an unusual microbiological finding in this situation. Through numerous case studies, it has been reported that some 25-80% of patients with a \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus bovis\u003C/em\u003E infection will have a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolorectal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E. If a positive culture is obtained, an urgent colonoscopy is required. \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus bovis\u003C/em\u003E commonly causes endocarditis and hepatobiliary infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatocellular cancer\u003C/strong\u003E, is less likely to be associated with Streptococcus bovis infection. While hepatocellular cancer may present with fever, it is not typically linked to Streptococcus bovis infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely as well. Streptococcus bovis is not commonly associated with gastric cancer. In cases of gastric cancer, patients may present with symptoms such as abdominal pain, weight loss, and nausea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is plausible but incorrect. Although renal cell carcinoma can present with fever due to paraneoplastic syndromes or secondary infections, it is not typically associated with Streptococcus bovis infection. Renal cell carcinoma is most often found as an incidental finding on imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholangiocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely to be associated with Streptococcus bovis infection. Cholangiocarcinoma may present with symptoms such as jaundice, abdominal pain, and weight loss, but it is not commonly linked to Streptococcus bovis infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Streptococcus bovis infection is often associated with colorectal cancer."],"references":["Tsai CE, Chiu CT, Rayner CK, Wu KL, Chiu YC, et al. Associated factors in\u00a0Streptococcus bovis\u00a0bacteremia and colorectal cancer. Kaohsiung J Med Sci. 2016;32(4):196-200. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1016/j.kjms.2016.03.003","Vaska VL, Faoagali JL. Streptococcus bovis bacteraemia: identification within organism complex and association with endocarditis and colonic malignancy. Pathology. 2009;41(2):183-6. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18972318/","Pompilio A, Bonaventura GD, Gherardi G. An Overview on\u00a0Streptococcus bovis/Streptococcus equinus\u00a0Complex Isolates: Identification to the Species/Subspecies Level and Antibiotic Resistance. Int J Mol Sci. 2019;20(3):480. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6386949/","SA Health. Surgical Antimicrobial prophylaxis clinical guideline [online]. Government of South Australia. 2017. Available from: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/6bb523804358edbd883b9ef2cadc00ab/Surgical%2BAntimicrobial%2BProphylaxis_v2.0+July+2020.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-6bb523804358edbd883b9ef2cadc00ab-nzp5dpB."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27644"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2598"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27644"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-16T15:21:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-01T15:56:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2598"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42700"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationship